The rain tapped against the window like tiny fingers demanding attention. Sam lay face-down on the couch, their tears soaking into the embroidered pillow Gram had made years ago.

"Want to talk about it?" Gram asked, settling into her rocking chair.

"My life is ruined," Sam mumbled into the pillow, voice muffled and dramatic. "Maya said my drawing was 'just okay.' It's the worst day ever."

Gram smiled gently. "Sounds like you might be exaggerating just a bit."

Sam turned their head, eyes red. "But it hurts!"

"I know, sweet pea. Come here." She patted the seat beside her. "Let me tell you something about love."

Sam shuffled over, clutching the damp pillow.

"When I was your age, I thought 'love' was just a word people threw around—like when your uncle says he's 'starving' before dinner, or when I say this old rocker is 'the best seat in the world.' I thought everyone was exaggerating."

Gram stared out at the gray sky. "Then one summer afternoon, a thunderstorm rolled in while my mother was away. I was terrified. I hid under my blanket, convinced the clouds were angry. But when Mama came home, she didn't laugh at my fear. She sat with me, her hand on my back, and said, 'Love is like those clouds, Ellie. It can seem dark and far away, but it's really full of light and water and life. It holds so much more than you can see.'"

"She stayed with me until the storm passed, her presence softening the thunder the way a pillow softens a fall. That day, I learned love isn't just a word—it's choosing to be there, even when someone's feelings seem silly. It's showing up."

Sam sniffed. "So Maya doesn't love me?"

"Maybe she just doesn't understand your art yet. But love—real love—is knowing that one person's opinion doesn't change your worth. It's me sitting here with you. It's you being brave enough to create again tomorrow."

The child looked at the pillow in their lap, at the stitched flowers their grandmother had carefully sewn. Each tiny stitch was a small, deliberate act of care.

"Love is in the stitches?" Sam asked quietly.

Gram nodded. "Love is in all the quiet places. The stitches, the staying, the listening. It's not loud or flashy. It's just... there. Holding you."

Sam leaned against Gram's shoulder. Outside, the clouds began to break apart, revealing patches of blue. The pillow felt softer now, the room warmer. And somehow, the hurt didn't seem quite so big anymore.

